Comment: A opening move I'm quite accustomed to, the King's Pawn Opening.
This is always my response, to King's Pawn, the King's Pawn Game.
White plays the Bishop's Opening. I already know white is planning to see if I fall for the 'checkmate in three moves' strategy, but I never fall for that anymore.
I respond with another move I'm popular with, the Bishop's Opening, Berlin Defence, which pretty much ruins any hope for a checkmate on f7.
This is not a opening in the book, so the book ends early.
Black pulls out the other knight.
Another common move. This either usually ends in a bishop, knight exchange or white retreats the bishop.
I open myself up for castling king-side.
Moment of truth...
Moment of truth...
...and white retreats the bishop.
Another common move I make. I want to drive back the bishop further.

Normally, this is a good move. You castle and protect your king further. Computer analysis views this as a inaccuracy. I couldn't understand this at first, but it didn't take me long to see why. There are 2 white pieces focused on the black e5 pawn, but only 1 black piece focused on the pawn. The result will be a +1 material point advantage for white. Although not much of a advantage, it is still an advantage.

After what I saw earlier, I expected white to retreat his bishop again.
I was quite correct.
Yet another popular move by black. I bring my bishop out to attack the queen, and the bishop is protected by the knight. Of course, white will protect it.
I was actually expecting white to play 11. f3, but this move works to.
I bring a strong attack that involves my knight and queen. It's not likely though that I would get a material advantage.
I'm not surprised white didn't play 13. Bxd5, but why Bd4 when white could castle? The computer analysis does view this as a mistake and that a king-side castle was the best move.

I decide to protect my knight just in case white does decide to attack. I did not see a possible advantage though. 13. ... Nf4 14. Be5 Nxg2+ 15. Kf1 ... This sequence would of not only gave me back my material advantage, but also would give me an advantage in position on the board, but again, I missed the opportunity.
